			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2015</a> paper:</span><br><i>An empirical study on simplification of business process modeling languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/EricUmuhoza.html">Eric Umuhoza</a>, <a href="../profile/MarcoBrambilla.html">Marco Brambilla</a>, <a href="../profile/DavideRipamonti.html">Davide Ripamonti</a>, <a href="../profile/JordiCabot.html">Jordi Cabot</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2814251.2814254">10.1145/2814251.2814254</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagM">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s primary contribution is an empirical study evaluating language simplification effects.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It concerns redesign/simplification choices in the design of a modeling language.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> Simplification is framed as adapting and maintaining a language for practical use over time.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> Business process modeling languages function as domain-specific languages for process modeling.
</li></ul></li></ul>
